WEBVTT

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hello, and welcome.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.600
In this video, I will explain my Enterprise-Grade SaaS Management Platform project.

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:18.800
In this project, I utilized Python and the Django framework to develop a management portal.

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:26.733
I adopted a monolith-first architecture for the backend to facilitate rapid and agile frontend development.

00:00:26.733 --> 00:00:39.266
While microservices are typically preferred for large-scale applications, starting with a well-structured monolith is the ideal approach for the initial stages of a complex system.

00:00:39.266 --> 00:00:46.733
It establishes a working foundation, making the eventual transition to microservices much smoother.

00:00:46.733 --> 00:00:51.733
But before diving into the project details, let me briefly introduce myself.

00:00:52.233 --> 00:00:54.033
I am Muhammad Husain Aboutalebi.

00:00:54.033 --> 00:01:06.299
I hold a degree in Mechanical Engineering from Amirkabir University of Technology (Tehran Polytechnic), but I have never let a paper degree define my limits.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:13.800
Driven by a deep passion for technology, I am a self-taught, multidisciplinary engineer.

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:22.900
I have years of hands-on experience programming across various languages and frameworks to build end-to-end software solutions.

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:38.233
Additionally, my expertise includes crafting intuitive UI/UX designs and developing artificial intelligence models using machine learning, deep learning, and reinforcement learning.

00:01:38.233 --> 00:01:46.066
First, to demonstrate the backend, let me activate the Python virtual environment and start the local server.

00:01:49.466 --> 00:01:54.066
Next, I’ll open the browser and navigate to the backend’s local URL.

00:01:54.066 --> 00:02:00.800
As you can see, the portal requires authentication to verify permissions before granting access.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:07.433
I’ve built the portal with three display modes—light, dark, and system—to enhance usability.

00:02:09.133 --> 00:02:12.166
Now, I’ll enter my email and password.

00:02:34.766 --> 00:02:38.100
The first view in the portal is the user dashboard.

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:45.633
This layout is dynamic, adapting to the specific roles and permissions defined by administrators.

00:02:45.633 --> 00:02:50.966
The primary goal is to provide a high-level overview of all data models.

00:02:50.966 --> 00:03:02.733
Since the backend handles diverse modules—such as dating, e-commerce, fitness tracking, and a library—this dashboard balances comprehensive reporting with a user-friendly experience.

00:03:02.733 --> 00:03:12.866
To verify that the frontend portal is actively communicating with the backend, let’s monitor the logs on the local development server.

00:03:15.033 --> 00:03:25.033
Navigating between modules in the portal is seamless. Clicking a module in the left sidebar instantly reveals its associated data models.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:32.833
Sorting, filtering, and searching through model records—such as user accounts—is straightforward and intuitive.

00:04:01.533 --> 00:04:18.900
You can also add new users by simply clicking the plus button. Overall, the portal provides a complete set of CRUD operations, putting all necessary data interactions right at your fingertips.

00:04:37.233 --> 00:04:43.133
The OTP, or One-Time Password, model stores the codes used to verify user authentication.

00:04:43.133 --> 00:04:49.966
These verification codes can be dispatched by either our current monolith-first backend or a dedicated microservice.

00:04:52.233 --> 00:04:59.300
The next module in the backend is the REST API. First, I’ll navigate to the API documentation.

00:05:02.066 --> 00:05:12.900
On the left, there is a sidebar listing all available APIs. I’ve grouped the endpoints by feature, following Domain-Driven Design principles.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:17.733
On the right, you’ll find the interactive section to test the API calls.

00:05:22.366 --> 00:05:28.400
There are several configuration options available to further customize the API interface.

00:05:30.333 --> 00:05:35.700
You can download the API documentation in both JSON and YAML formats.

00:05:36.766 --> 00:05:43.800
To enhance the user experience, the interface supports seamless toggling between light and dark themes.

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:51.800
In the left sidebar, expanding a category reveals its grouped endpoints and their HTTP methods.

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:59.566
Selecting an endpoint opens its full details and an interactive request console in the right-hand panel.

00:06:00.666 --> 00:06:08.533
As your API grows or spans multiple versions, you can easily search across all endpoints and descriptions.

00:06:08.533 --> 00:06:14.733
Simply click the search field in the left sidebar, type a keyword, and select your result.

00:06:15.766 --> 00:06:23.000
To test the API in real time, simply select an endpoint from the left sidebar and click the ‘Test Request’ button.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:37.266
The interface provides everything you need to consume the endpoint correctly, including required fields, expected responses, and ready-to-use client code snippets for languages like Python and C#.

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:48.233
You can also use the quick search feature directly within the test console. This greatly improves usability and speeds up your testing workflow.

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:56.933
To simplify the testing process, you can use filters to control exactly what is displayed in the interface.

00:06:59.900 --> 00:07:09.433
Because some backend endpoints require authentication, you can set a Bearer token directly in the interface to test protected requests.

00:07:18.733 --> 00:07:26.366
You can also change the API code snippets to match your client-side language, such as Python, C#, or Dart.

